If we treat fluency as “the ability to operate naturally within a particular medium, constraint, or domain,” then there are far more than just language fluency. One way to organize them is by the kinds of environments an intelligent system has to navigate.

Foundational Fluencies

These underpin almost everything else.

* Reality Fluency — Respecting physical constraints and causality.
* Semantic Fluency — Moving meaning across representations without losing intent.
* Linguistic Fluency — Using language effectively.
* Logical Fluency — Following valid reasoning.
* Mathematical Fluency — Quantitative reasoning.
* Computational Fluency — Thinking in algorithms, abstraction, and automation.
* Temporal Fluency — Reasoning across timescales and distinguishing enduring patterns from transient ones.
* Spatial Fluency — Navigating physical and conceptual spaces.

